lead_paragraph: After nearly two years of near-zero interest rates, the Federal Reserve signaled that it would probably raise them in March. Jerome H. Powell, the Fed chair, said officials no longer thought that America’s rapidly healing economy needed so much support, given that inflation is running far above policymakers’ target and the tight labor market. By making it more expensive to borrow money to buy a house or car, the Fed hopes the higher interest rates will cool demand and eventually help rein in inflation.
